node.text:
I remember when building a presentation felt like the most clunky, arduous, homework-ey thing. Anyone remember the days of resenting presentations 👋? 

Fast forward to today, and I create all my presentations in @canva. At Business Class, we've built beautiful presentations for everything from brand guidelines to company culture, customer personas (in Business Class we call these Perfect Passengers), media kits, and internal reports. 

The magic of presentations is that not only are you articulating something to others, but by telling a visual story, you're articulating it to yourself as well, giving you the opportunity to reflect and take pride in what you've achieved. Super curious — have you used @canva presentations? 

#EnjoyPresentations #Ad #MadeWithCanva

node.text:
🤔 I get this question a lot: How do I scale my business when I can’t afford to hire someone? 🤔

Here are a few questions you should ask yourself to decide if you have a sustainable business that can keep growing:

Is this a business or a hobby? A lot of times people get the two confused. A business has the opportunity to scale––it doesn’t have to be a huge opportunity or even a big business, but you need to assess whether or not there are enough customers out there who want your product. If so, your job is to reach them, keep up with demand, and keep them happy. 

Is the demand exceeding your ability to supply? If you hire an intern to process shipments and respond to customers, will your additional free time allow you to drive more sales? 

Do you love it? On the outside, entrepreneurship can seem sexy. The truth is that it’s not. If you don’t love it, consider scaling down your efforts and keep your passion as a side hustle. As Billie Eilish says in her new song “things I once enjoyed just keep me employed now.” Keep an eye out for that and don’t kill your passion to make a buck. 

If you could hire someone to help you and your business right now, what would they do?

*please read before you mistakenly congratulate me* 

1 in 8 women struggle with infertility (👋 me here). 

1 in 4 experience miscarriage (👋 hi it’s me again). 

These experiences are so common, yet rarely discussed. And it’s often not clear how to get the right information or care, let alone how to afford it.

This is why I am so excited to be an investor in Kindbody - a women-led company changing the face of women’s health and fertility care. They have warm, welcoming locations across the country offering fertility, gynecology, and wellness services at more affordable prices. They are on a mission to broaden the fertility conversation, increase access to care, and deliver a more inclusive patient experience. 

In addition, @businessclass is now offering fertility benefits for egg freezing, IVF and more to our full-time employees. 

Check out @kindbody to learn more about their services and how they can support you in your own fertility or family-building journey.

node.text:
In this week’s newsletter I talk about why you should ask for criticism and embrace it like a hug.

The harsh reality is that we’re often so close to our ideas and creations that we lose perspective, either thinking our work is total trash or, possibly worse, that our trash work is totally great. 

Most of us don’t proactively solicit critique. It feels masochistic –– isn’t it enough that we flagellate ourselves while FOMO-ing at the mouth as we scroll through everyone else’s seemingly perfect business/work/talent reels? The answer is no. 

Critique is like therapy for your work. Don’t take it all at face value, but plot the feedback in your brain like a heatmap and build new neural pathways to objectively examine yourself and your creations on the regular. 

How has constructive criticism helped you in the past? Share with me in the comments, and if you’d like the full scoop, sign up for my weekly newsletter via the link in my bio!

node.text:
I talk a lot about business finance both in my newsletter (sign up with the link in my bio) and in @BusinessClass, but today I want to talk about personal finance. Your money. Because it doesn’t matter how much your company makes or how big your paycheck is, if you don’t manage your personal scrilla, you’re shit out of luck.

There was a time many years ago that I came upon a windfall of cash. I was young, naive, didn’t even have a credit card, and went, overnight, from eating $9 San Francisco burritos to buying dozens of oysters and fizzy water in glass bottles. 

You know how when you get pants that are a little too big you tend to fill them up? Get a bigger apartment and somehow end up with more shit and wonder how it got there? Well, that’s what happens when you make money. 

I understand that it’s a privilege to say any of this and at the risk of sounding tone deaf, I want to impress upon you that with money, there is a point of diminishing returns.

I said in that book I wrote 7 years ago that cash is king, and then I forgot. Cash is mother fucking king and queen and ace and all the shit. 

Don’t let your life be about chasing it, but instead save it and invest it in things that will make your money make more money or bring you joy –– just not too much of it. Because true joy has absolutely nothing to do with oysters.

node.text:
As a now-veteran entrepreneur, I have battle scars to show for it. Don’t get me wrong: the rises, falls, and bounce-backs have been a blast. But the stress that came with it all has taken its toll. Being a walking stress case for so many years, I was abusing my face and body… with my mind. 

When science-based @muradskincare approached me to be a guest editor for their digital magazine, Well Connected, I was thrilled to contribute. 

The link between wellness and our skin health is crucial. Because no matter how much expensive cream or how many steps our nightly routine has, it can’t beat stress. What they’re doing over at Well Connected to connect the dots between science and wellness is so refreshing. Woo woo meets legit doctors and experts? Sign me up. (oh yeah, I already did). #wellconectedbymurad #muradeditor
